No, there is not. [`String.match()` returns][1]:

&gt; An `Array` whose contents depend on the presence or absence of the global (`g`) flag, or `null` if no matches are found.

So you could do something like:

    if (bar_variable = line.match(/foo{bar}/)) {
      console.log(bar_variable)
    }

To avoid a global symbol you could do something like this, but it does make it a bit uglier:

    {
      let bar_variable;
      if (bar_variable = line.match(/foo{bar}/)) {
        console.log(bar_variable);
      }
    }

As far as I know you can&#39;t do `if (let x = ...)` but I could be wrong.

  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/match

